#compdef taskctl
# =============================================================================
# taskctl — Yevhen Terentiev's "concurrent task runner, developer's
#            routine tasks automation toolkit — simple modern
#            alternative to GNU Make."  A YAML-configured task runner
#            that executes tasks concurrently with dependency
#            resolution, output formatting, and interactive task
#            selection.  taskctl reads tasks.yaml (or taskctl.yaml)
#            from the current directory and provides:
#              - Task definitions (shell command + args + env + dir)
#              - Pipeline definitions (DAG of tasks with depends_on
#                edges resolved via topological sort)
#              - Context definitions (per-task shell + env + working
#                directory)
#              - Watcher definitions (file-watch triggers that
#                auto-rerun tasks on change)
#              - Output formats: raw (no decoration), prefixed
#                (task-name prefix per line), cockpit (split-screen
#                multi-pane output for parallel tasks)
#              - Concurrent execution (multiple tasks in parallel,
#                up to OS process limit)
#              - Dry-run mode (show what would execute without
#                running)
#              - Interactive task selection via manifoldco/promptui
#                when no task argument is given (`taskctl run`
#                prompts user to pick a task from the configured list)
#            Designed for developers tired of writing Bash scripts
#            wrapped in Makefile recipes; positioned as a "modern
#            Make alternative" alongside Just, Taskfile.dev, mage,
#            and Earthly.
#
# Author:  Yevhen Terentiev — Ukrainian software engineer; created
#          taskctl as a personal "I want Make but with YAML and
#          concurrency" project in 2019, gained community traction
#          quickly.
# Source:  https://github.com/taskctl/taskctl
# CLI:     cmd/cmd.go (uses urfave/cli/v2 for argv parsing +
#                       manifoldco/promptui for interactive task
#                       selection when no task argument is given)
# Library: manifoldco/promptui
#          ("Interactive prompt for command-line applications" —
#           Manifold's interactive-prompt Go library; the Go
#           parallel to Rust's dialoguer R518 and TypeScript-Node's
#           Inquirer.js R520; predates Charm's huh R543 by 5+
#           years.)
# License: Apache-2.0
# Status:  Active — 323+ stars on taskctl/taskctl; promptui itself
#          is 6388+ stars on manifoldco/promptui (continuous
#          development since 2017 by Manifold Inc — Manifold was
#          a SaaS startup acquired by Snyk in 2020; promptui
#          remains community-maintained at the original repo).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — GO CROSSES TO 46
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 46TH Go CLI library variant.  Go climbs from 45 to 46 documented
# libraries (manifoldco/promptui via taskctl).  New leaderboard:
# Rust=46, Go=46, TypeScript-Node=45 (Rust+Go TWO-WAY TIE AT 46 —
# sixth two-way tie at 46-or-above of this round-sequence).  Taxonomy
# now spans 294 cross-language CLI library variants across 71
# documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 3 leader bumps (R554 crossterm Rust → R555 promptui Go
# THIS → expected R556 TS-Node) following 1 new lang (R553 Yorick).
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 2 (INTERACTIVE PROMPTS) within Go to
# THREE documented prompt libraries spanning three generations:
#
#   * Gen 1 (2017): manifoldco/promptui (THIS R555 — PROTOTYPE-FIRST
#                    design where each prompt is a Go struct that
#                    you populate and .Run())
#   * Gen 2 (2018): AlecAivazis/survey R519 (per-question API via
#                    AskOne(), schema-based)
#   * Gen 3 (2024): charmbracelet/huh R543 (forms-first design built
#                    on bubbletea)
#
# Three POLAR-DIFFERENT approaches to interactive prompts within
# the Go ecosystem now documented:
#   * promptui:  PROTOTYPE-OBJECT style — each prompt is a struct
#                 (`promptui.Select{Label: ..., Items: ...}`)
#                 populated and Run()
#   * survey:    PER-QUESTION FUNCTION style — `AskOne(&question,
#                 &answer)`
#   * huh:       FORMS-FIRST DECLARATIVE style — multi-field forms
#                 via NewForm/NewGroup composition
#
# Go is now the FIRST documented language with THREE GENERATIONS of
# prompt-library design documented (parallel to TS-Node's 4
# prompt libraries: Inquirer.js R520 + @clack/prompts R512 +
# @inquirer/prompts R520-rewrite + enquirer R544).  Cross-language
# prompt-library matrix:
#   * Rust:    dialoguer R518 + inquire R514 + cliclack R510 (3)
#   * Go:      promptui R555 + survey R519 + huh R543 (3)
#   * TS-Node: Inquirer.js + @clack/prompts + @inquirer/prompts +
#               enquirer R544 (4)
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS promptui AND WHY IS IT THE 46TH GO CLI LIBRARY?
#
# promptui (https://github.com/manifoldco/promptui, 6388+ stars) is
# **Manifold Inc's "Interactive prompt for command-line
# applications"** — a Go library for building interactive terminal
# prompts (single-line input, single-select list, multi-select
# list, password input, confirm prompt).  Created in 2017 by
# Manifold, a SaaS-orchestration startup (later acquired by Snyk in
# 2020) — promptui was extracted from Manifold's internal CLI
# tooling and released openly.  After Manifold's acquisition,
# promptui has been community-maintained at the original repository.
#
# promptui's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. PROTOTYPE-OBJECT API — promptui prompts are Go STRUCTS that
#      you POPULATE with configuration then call `.Run()`:
#
#          prompt := promptui.Select{
#              Label: "Select Day",
#              Items: []string{"Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday",
#                              "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday",
#                              "Sunday"},
#              Templates: &promptui.SelectTemplates{
#                  Label:    "{{ . }}?",
#                  Active:   "▸ {{ . | cyan }}",
#                  Inactive: "  {{ . | cyan }}",
#                  Selected: "▸ {{ . | red | cyan }}",
#              },
#              Stdin: os.Stdin,
#          }
#          _, result, err := prompt.Run()
#          if err != nil { return err }
#          fmt.Printf("You chose %s\n", result)
#
#      Compare:
#         * survey R519:   `survey.AskOne(&survey.Select{...},
#                            &answer)` — function-based, similar
#         * huh R543:       `huh.NewSelect[string]()...` — fluent
#                            builder
#         * enquirer R544 (TS): JavaScript class `new Select({...}).
#                                run()` — similar prototype-object
#         * dialoguer R518 (Rust): `dialoguer::Select::new()` —
#                                similar builder
#      promptui is the FIRST documented Go CLI library with
#      prototype-object prompt configuration.
#
#   2. GO-text/template TEMPLATE-BASED RENDERING — promptui uses
#      Go's `text/template` package for customizing prompt
#      appearance:
#
#          Templates: &promptui.SelectTemplates{
#              Label:    "{{ . }}?",
#              Active:   "▸ {{ . | cyan }}",
#              Inactive: "  {{ . | cyan }}",
#              Selected: "▸ {{ . | red | cyan }}",
#              Details:  `--------- Day ----------
#                         {{ "Description:" | faint }}
#                         {{ .Description }}`,
#          }
#
#      Each prompt phase (Label, Active, Inactive, Selected, Details,
#      Help) has its own template string.  Custom template functions
#      (like the `cyan`, `red`, `faint` color filters) are
#      registered via promptui's built-in functions.  Compare:
#         * survey R519:   limited templating (color/icon
#                            configuration only)
#         * huh R543:       lipgloss Style for theming
#         * enquirer R544 (TS): JavaScript symbols+styles config
#         * dialoguer R518 (Rust): Theme trait abstraction
#      FIRST documented prompt library that uses GENERAL-PURPOSE
#      TEMPLATE LANGUAGE (Go text/template) for prompt rendering.
#
#   3. KEYS DRIVER — promptui's keyboard handling is configurable
#      via a `Keys` struct:
#
#          prompt.Keys = &promptui.SelectKeys{
#              Next:     promptui.Key{Code: readline.CharNext,
#                                     Display: "↓"},
#              Prev:     promptui.Key{Code: readline.CharPrev,
#                                     Display: "↑"},
#              PageUp:   promptui.Key{Code: readline.CharForw,
#                                     Display: "→"},
#              PageDown: promptui.Key{Code: readline.CharBackward,
#                                     Display: "←"},
#              Search:   promptui.Key{Code: '/', Display: "/"},
#          }
#
#      Compare every other documented prompt library — none have
#      explicit Keys-binding struct configuration.  Compare:
#         * survey R519:   fixed key bindings
#         * huh R543:      fixed key bindings (Tab/Shift-Tab)
#         * enquirer R544: customizable via prototype override
#         * dialoguer R518: fixed (use console-rs/console for raw)
#      FIRST documented prompt library with first-class
#      configurable-keybinding struct.
#
#   4. chzyer/readline BACKEND — promptui uses chzyer/readline
#      (the documented R??? Go readline library) as its keyboard
#      input backend.  This means promptui:
#         - Inherits readline's full line-editor features (history,
#           ctrl-A, ctrl-E, ctrl-U, ctrl-W cursor manipulation)
#         - Inherits readline's UTF-8 input handling
#         - Inherits readline's terminal raw-mode setup
#      Compare:
#         * survey R519:    uses go-isatty + own raw-mode setup
#         * huh R543:        built on bubbletea (different stack)
#         * enquirer R544 (TS): uses readline npm package
#         * dialoguer R518 (Rust): uses console-rs/console
#      FIRST documented Go prompt library that builds on
#      chzyer/readline (the Go GNU-Readline reimplementation).
#
#   5. SEARCH-IN-LIST PROMPT — promptui's `Select` prompt has
#      built-in search-as-you-type filtering when `Searcher`
#      function is provided:
#
#          searcher := func(input string, index int) bool {
#              item := items[index]
#              name := strings.Replace(strings.ToLower(item.Name),
#                                     " ", "", -1)
#              input = strings.Replace(strings.ToLower(input),
#                                     " ", "", -1)
#              return strings.Contains(name, input)
#          }
#
#          prompt := promptui.Select{
#              Label:    "Select a country",
#              Items:    countries,
#              Templates: &templates,
#              Size:     4,
#              Searcher: searcher,
#          }
#
#      User presses `/` to enter search mode, types substring,
#      list filters in real time.  Compare:
#         * survey R519:    has `WithFilter()` callback
#         * huh R543:        has filtering support via Options
#         * fzf:             dedicated fuzzy-finder (not a prompt
#                             library)
#      FIRST documented Go prompt library with first-class search-
#      filter callback via Searcher function.
#
# promptui's relationship to other documented Go CLI libraries:
#
#   * Like survey R519     — interactive prompts (same axis,
#                             different design — promptui is
#                             prototype-object, survey is per-
#                             question function)
#   * Like huh R543         — interactive prompts (different
#                             generation — promptui 2017,
#                             huh 2024)
#   * Like chzyer/readline  — promptui builds on readline (same
#                             dependency)
#   * Unlike all of the above — PROTOTYPE-OBJECT API +
#                                GO-template-based rendering +
#                                CONFIGURABLE keys + chzyer/
#                                readline-backed + first-class
#                                search-in-list.
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Rust:    dialoguer R518 (builder-style prompts;
#                     similar generation 2017-2018)
#         * TS-Node: enquirer R544 (prototype-based class API;
#                     similar prototype-object pattern)
#     promptui completes the FIRST-GENERATION INTERACTIVE-PROMPT
#     triple across the top three languages (R518 dialoguer Rust +
#     R555 promptui Go + R520 Inquirer.js TS-Node — all 2017-2018
#     vintage prompt libraries with prototype/builder APIs).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE taskctl CLI — urfave/cli/v2 + promptui Composition
#
# taskctl's argv parser is urfave/cli/v2 (the established Go CLI
# framework that pre-dates cobra):
#
#     return &cli.App{
#         Name:                 "taskctl",
#         Usage:                "modern task runner",
#         Version:              version,
#         EnableBashCompletion: true,
#         BashComplete: func(c *cli.Context) {
#             // Dynamic suggestions from loaded YAML config
#             ...
#         },
#         Flags: []cli.Flag{
#             &cli.BoolFlag{Name: "debug", Aliases: []string{"d"}, ...},
#             &cli.PathFlag{Name: "config", Aliases: []string{"c"}, ...},
#             &cli.StringFlag{Name: "output", Aliases: []string{"o"}, ...},
#             &cli.BoolFlag{Name: "raw", Aliases: []string{"r"}, ...},
#             &cli.BoolFlag{Name: "cockpit", ...},
#             &cli.BoolFlag{Name: "quiet", Aliases: []string{"q"}, ...},
#             &cli.StringSliceFlag{Name: "set", ...},
#             &cli.BoolFlag{Name: "dry-Run", ...},
#             &cli.BoolFlag{Name: "summary", Aliases: []string{"s"}, ...},
#         },
#         Commands: []*cli.Command{
#             newRunCommand(), newInitCommand(), newListCommand(),
#             newGraphCommand(), newCompletionCommand(),
#         },
#     }
#
# When `taskctl run` is invoked WITHOUT a task argument, taskctl
# uses promptui's `Select` prompt to let the user interactively
# pick a task from the YAML-configured list — this is the
# headline promptui usage in taskctl.
#
# Distinct from every other documented Go CLI library on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. PROTOTYPE-OBJECT API — Every other documented Go prompt
#      library uses function calls (survey's AskOne, huh's NewForm
#      builder).  promptui uses Go STRUCTS as prompt prototypes
#      that you populate then `.Run()`.  FIRST documented Go
#      prompt library with prototype-object configuration.
#
#   2. GO-text/template TEMPLATE-BASED RENDERING — Every other
#      documented Go prompt library uses theme structs (huh's
#      lipgloss Theme), fixed visual styles (survey), or no
#      theming (other libraries).  promptui uses Go's text/template
#      package for prompt appearance customization.  FIRST
#      documented prompt library using a general-purpose template
#      language for rendering.
#
#   3. CONFIGURABLE KEYS STRUCT — Every other documented prompt
#      library has fixed key bindings or library-internal
#      customization.  promptui exposes a `Keys` struct on each
#      prompt allowing per-prompt key remapping.  FIRST documented
#      prompt library with first-class configurable-keybinding
#      struct.
#
#   4. chzyer/readline BACKEND — Every other documented Go prompt
#      library builds on different stacks (bubbletea, go-isatty,
#      custom).  promptui builds on chzyer/readline (the Go GNU-
#      Readline reimplementation).  FIRST documented Go prompt
#      library built on chzyer/readline.
#
#   5. SEARCH-IN-LIST PROMPT — Every other documented Go prompt
#      library has limited or no filtering.  promptui's Select
#      accepts a `Searcher` function for live filtering as user
#      types substring.  FIRST documented Go prompt library with
#      first-class Searcher callback.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/taskctl/taskctl/blob/master/cmd/cmd.go
# urfave/cli/v2 App definition.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

local -a commands=(
    'run:run a pipeline or task (interactive task selection if no arg)'
    'init:generate example tasks.yaml in current directory'
    'list:list configured contexts, pipelines, tasks, watchers'
    'graph:show pipeline DAG as Mermaid or DOT'
    'completion:generate shell completion script'
)

_arguments -s -C \
    '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[print help and exit]' \
    '(-v --version)'{-v,--version}'[print version and exit]' \
    '(-d --debug)'{-d,--debug}'[enable debug logging]' \
    '(-c --config)'{-c+,--config=}'[config file (default tasks.yaml or taskctl.yaml)]:file:_files -g "*.(yaml|yml)"' \
    '(-o --output)'{-o+,--output=}'[output format]:format:(raw prefixed cockpit)' \
    '(-r --raw)'{-r,--raw}'[shortcut for --output=raw]' \
    '--cockpit[shortcut for --output=cockpit]' \
    '(-q --quiet)'{-q,--quiet}'[quiet mode (suppress output)]' \
    '*--set=[set global variable as KEY=VALUE]:variable:' \
    '--dry-Run[dry-run mode (show without executing)]' \
    '(-s --summary)'{-s,--summary}'[show execution summary]' \
    '1: :->cmd' \
    '*:: :->args' \
    && ret=0

case "$state" in
    cmd)
        _describe -t commands 'taskctl subcommand' commands && ret=0
        ;;
    args)
        case "${words[1]}" in
            list)
                _arguments '1:type:(contexts pipelines tasks watchers)' && ret=0
                ;;
            completion)
                _arguments '1:shell:(bash zsh fish)' && ret=0
                ;;
            graph)
                _arguments '1:pipeline:' && ret=0
                ;;
            run)
                _arguments '*:task or pipeline:' && ret=0
                ;;
        esac
        ;;
esac

return ret
